nt element-image\" data-media-id=\"76769b5d5b91253adc2690004be7df9c614c4d07\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2014/12/17/1418831193576/Cathy-Henderson-artist-wh-019.jpg\" alt=\"Cathy Henderson, artist, who has died aged 51\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Cathy Henderson produced an exhibition of portraits of hospital workers</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>My sister, Cathy Henderson, who has died aged 51, was an artist who was gaining increasing recognition in Ireland and beyond.</p> <p>In early 2012 she was selected as co-designer, with Robert Ballagh, of the <a href=\"http://www.lockout1913.ie/national-tapestry-project\" title=\"\">1913 Lockout Tapestry</a>, a big collaborative project between the National College of Art and Design (NCAD) in Dublin and the Irish trade union Siptu to commemorate the centenary of the 1913 Dublin Lockout, in which more than 100,000 people engaged in a battle for workers’ rights. Despite her diagnosis of cancer the same year, Cathy continued working on the tapestry, which involved 30 separate panels created by 200 adult volunteers and 60 schoolchildren, until its completion in October 2013. The tapestry continues to be displayed at various venues throughout Ireland.</p> <p>Cathy was born in London, the daughter of Peter Henderson, a lecturer in occupational psychology, and his wife, Mary (nee Topham), an artist. She grew up in Staffordshire, Belfast and Bangor before spending a year in Paris. Instead of taking up a place at the École des Beaux-Arts, she went to Dublin to study at the NCAD. She graduated in 1993 after a summer at the studio of the graphic designer Milton Glaser in Manhattan.</p> <p>In 1996 Cathy worked at the Lyric theatre, Belfast, producing a large series of paintings documenting the actors and crew. In 1998 she and her husband, David Gregg, produced an audio documentary on the Lisdoonvarna matchmaking festival in Co Clare, which was broadcast on BBC Radio 4 and nominated for a Sony award.</p> <p>In 2002 Cathy was involved in a serious road accident. Many months in hospital followed, with numerous operations to reconstruct a shattered leg. During that time she noticed portraits of various hospital luminaries along the corridors, but recognised none of them. She decided to redress the balance with a series of paintings of the hospital workers she saw every day, which were exhibited at St James’s hospital, Dublin in 2009.</p> <p>Cathy extended this concept and painted a series of portraits of Dublin city council’s cleansing department workers, exhibited as Below the Surface, at the Mermaid arts centre, Bray, Co Wicklow, in 2007. Both these exhibitions included audio recordings, engineered by her husband, of the subjects talking about their work.</p> <p>Despite her disability Cathy travelled several times to the Canadian Arctic, working and exhibiting with Inuit artists. Her career included community art projects in that region as well as in Belfast, Dublin and New York. She also taught art in Irish prisons. Her work is in private and public collections, including the National Bank of Canada and Queen’s University Belfast.</p> <p>She is survived by David, me, my brother Michael, and our father. Our mother and brother Andrew predeceased her.</p>","internalOctopusCode":"9894942","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-01-01T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2211560","internalRevision":"13","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"<strong>Other lives:</strong> Artist who co-designed the 1913 Lockout Tapestry, which commemorated the Dublin battle for workers’ rights","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Cathy Henderson obituary","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","byline":"Stephen Henderson","commentable":"false","firstPublicationDate":"2014-12-17T16:20:28.682Z","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.