nddebate","webTitle":"Comment & debate","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"theguardian","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/mainsection/commentanddebate","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/mainsection/commentanddebate","sectionName":"From the Guardian"}]},{"id":"business/2014/dec/31/new-years-eve-mobile-phone-call-made-history","type":"article","sectionId":"business","webTitle":"New Year’s Day mobile phone call made history and started a new era","webPublicationDate":"2014-12-31T15:30:31Z","fields":{"main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"5f433cbbfb65590e1ab4cc0fd06e67380f0a10d7\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/31/1420039650769/41624bd3-a714-4e5f-8ec4-2683254e2461-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"'Hello Dad?\" Michael Harrison phones Sir Michael Harrison on 1 January 1985, on the 5kg Transportable Vodafone VT1.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">‘Hello Dad?’ Michael Harrison phones Sir Ernest Harrison on 1 January 1985, on the 5kg prototype Transportable Vodafone VT1.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Vodafone/PA</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>Thirty years ago, the son of Vodafone’s chairman Sir Ernest Harrison secretly ducked out of the family’s New Year’s Eve party. A few hours later, just after midnight and standing in the shadow of Big Ben in Parliament Square, he called home to wish his father Happy New Year – and that was the UK’s first ever mobile phone call.</p> <p>Michael Harrison had dragged the 5kg (11lb) briefcase-sized prototype phone with him to make the call in a dummy run hours before comedian Ernie Wise was due to make the first official mobile phone call from St Katherine’s Docks in London.</p> <p>In the call, Michael Harrison said: “Hi Dad. It’s Mike. This is the first-ever call made on a UK commercial mobile network.” On the other end of the line, champagne corks popped and photographers recorded the moment.</p> <p>Later that day, Wise – dressed in top hat and period costume – made the first official mobile call to Vodafone’s then headquarters above an Indian restaurant in Newbury, Berkshire.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"baeae44b76cd30cc006d1ff012a72de839186231\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/31/1420039763092/99989622-65fc-46c2-be50-2571f6ce3160-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"The Transportable Vodafone VT1.\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The Transportable Vodafone VT1.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Vodafone/PA</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Harrison’s Vodafone, a start-up from inside the wider Racal defence and electronics company, had beaten BT Cellnet to start the UK’s first mobile network by just nine days.</p> <p>By the end of 1985, more than 12,000 mobile phones had been sold for about £2,000 each (the equivalent of about £5,000 now). The phones were marketed in Saatchi &amp; Saatchi adverts featuring Ferrari-driving businessmen with the slogan: “You can be in when you’re out.”</p> <p>Today, Vodafone has 438 million customers around the world. The UK mobile phone industry made more £15.6bn in 2013, with more than 83 million people signed up – far more than the UK’s population of 64 million.</p> <p>Those users made 134bn calls and sent around 130bn texts last year.</p> <p>• This article was amended on 2 January 2015. The original headline wrongly stated that the phone call took place on New Year’s Eve, instead of early on New Year’s Day. The caption wrongly named the Vodafone chairman as Sir Michael Harrison, instead of Sir Ernest Harrison. The article also wrongly suggested that Ernie Wise’s call had been made a day after Michael Harrison’s, instead of the same day. These have been corrected.<br /></p>"