lmost double rivals at the next highest-paying bank, Bank of America Merrill Lynch.</p> <p>The statistics <a href=\"http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/30/us-banks-britain-pay-idUSKBN0K81B220141230?feedType=RSS&amp;feedName=everything&amp;virtualBrandChannel=11563\" title=\"Reuters\">compiled by Reuters</a> shed light on City pay practices as trade unions said workers <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2014/dec/30/british-workers-decade-wages-recover-tuc\" title=\"\">will have to wait until 2024 to make up the loss in their wages</a> since the 2008 crisis.</p> <p>Frances O’Grady, head of the TUC, said: “Risk-taking banks caused the global crash, yet while pay for the many has fallen every year since 2008, top bankers are still raking it in. It’s time their pay came out of the stratosphere and back to planet Earth. Let us make 2015 the year in which employees get a voice on remuneration committees.”</p> <p>Information on City pay has become available since the bailout of the banking sector which prompted the European Union to demand disclosures on bonuses and the salaries of so-called “code staff” – those deemed to be taking and managing risks. The most recent data compiled from 13 employers is for 2013 and does not include the period since those employees have come under the EU cap on bonuses, which restricts payouts to one times salary or twice if shareholders approve.</p> <p>The calculations by Reuters show large variations in pay among the 13 banks included in its survey of 2,600 employees. The £3m average of Goldman Sachs’ top staff compares with £1.4m at Barclays and £600,000 at Royal Bank of Scotland – which is 79%-owned by taxpayers.</p> <p>Campaigners for a transaction tax to be paid by banks said the data showed they were not making a contribution to society.</p> <p>“Even in a financial sector with grossly inflated pay, Goldman Sachs manages to shock with what it gives its top brass. But Goldmans is the tip of the iceberg – an under-taxed financial sector continues filling the pockets of its own in a way that is out of proportion to the contribution it makes to society,” a spokesman for the Robin Hood tax campaign said.</p> <p>The first year that information about pay was required was 2010, when Goldman Sachs’ average was £4m before it dipped to £1.8m and then started to rise again.</p> <p>The EU bonus cap, introduced at the start of 2014, has resulted in banks devising controversial allowances to prevent their top bankers losing out, handed out in addition to regular pay and bonuses. In 2014,<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/dec/26/banks-30m-bonus-cap-hsbc-barclays-lloyds-rbs-shares-eu\" title=\"\"> Britain’s four high street banks handed out £30m </a>in shares to a dozen or so of their top bankers – but it is not yet clear how Wall Street players have altered the pay of their London-based staff. Ross McEwan, the boss of RBS, was the single UK bank boss not to take an allowance last year, though he will take an allowance of £1m in shares for 2015.</p> <p>There may be further changes to pay deals for bankers in 2015 as the European Banking Authority – the pan-EU banking regulator – has concluded that the allowances breach the bonus cap. The Bank of England is opposed to the cap on bonuses and has so far agreed to the payouts of allowances, though the Bank governor, Mark Carney <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/nov/17/banking-culture-overhaul-mark-carney-bankers-pay\" title=\"\">has raised the idea that salaries could be docked </a>as a punishment for misconduct.</p>","internalOctopusCode":"9935107","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-01-01T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"true","internalPageCode":"2216634","internalRevision":"22","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"TUC describes pay as ‘stratospheric’ as Goldman Sachs high-flyers earn £3m average with £1.4m at Barclays and £600,000 at RBS","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Senior City bankers paid an averag