K this year. England, Wales and Northern Ireland endured their lowest temperatures the following night.</p> <p>Researchers suggest this year could be the UK’s warmest, as measured by the world’s oldest temperature record over almost 250 years.</p> <p>The 11 months from January to November have already been the warmest period on the Met Office’s Central England Temperature record.</p> <p>A spokesman for MeteoGroup said: “For New Year’s Eve night the temperatures will be down to about 4C or 5C , which will be the same for most parts of the UK. In the west and north temperatures could be around 7C so much milder than the previous few nights.</p> <p>“It will be a good evening to be out as it is mostly dry over much of England. The north and west might see some patchy rain, as will Scotland but it won’t be a bad night for being outside anywhere.”</p> <p>The Met Office warned that the weather is set to change from the current crisp winter days, with a rise in temperatures and more unsettled, windy weather.</p> <p>Through the course of New Year’s Day, it will gradually turn wet and windy across the whole of the country – but it should stay mild.</p>","internalOctopusCode":"9934902","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-01-01T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"true","internalPageCode":"2216572","internalRevision":"21","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"Cold weather to shift as Hogmanay revellers in Edinburgh will enjoy 10C with 11C in Dublin and temperatures well above zero around most of UK","allowUgc":"false","headline":"New Year’s Eve weather forecast: mild, largely dry, and probably quite fun","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","byline":"Press Association","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2014-12-31T10:14:29.721Z","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/31/1420020603121/47cb3586-f9f8-476a-ab50-2271ec50e351-140x84.jpeg","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/44gf7","wordcount":"454","shouldHideAd